"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584202","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-14","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office is aware of claims by Mr al-Faraj's family that ammunition produced in the UK was used in the incident that killed him. The UK Government takes decisions on all arms export licensing applications on the basis of close and careful consideration, assessing them against the EU and National Consolidated Arms Export Licensing Criteria, which includes an assessment of whether there is a clear risk that the items might be used for internal repression.</p><p>The Saudi Interior Ministry spokesman stated that Mr al-Faraj was suspected of previously killing security forces personnel and indicated that substantial arms and ammunition were found on the premises during the operation.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-10-14T13:28:59.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584202/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584202/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-15","Primetake","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations his Department has received on reports of the use of ammunition produced and exported by Primetake, a company based in Lincolnshire, to kill Abdul-Rahim al-Faraj by security forces in Saudi Arabia; and whether he plans to investigate such reports.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","46686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584203","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-14","<p>The UK is recognised as the world’s leading FinTech capital, with recent reports such as EY’s ‘UK FinTech: on the cutting edge’ and Deloitte’s ‘Connecting Global FinTech: Hub Review 2016’ placing the UK and London as the number one location for FinTech in the world.</p><p> </p><p>The government is determined to continue to help support UK FinTech firms as they innovate and grow, and wants to ensure that the UK remains the location of choice for FinTech firms. As such, we are continuing to implement a range of our previously announced policies which are designed to reduce barriers to entry for FinTechs, help industry accelerate the development of key FinTech initiatives and ease access to foreign markets. We are also assessing other initiatives which can further help support the growth of UK FinTech, in consultation with the industry.</p><p> </p><p>In July, we launched our second FinTech Bridge with the Republic of Korea – increasing the opportunities for trade and investment between our two nations on FinTech, and deepening regulatory and government collaboration.</p><p>Following the vote to leave the European Union, the government is engaging extensively with the sector. I will be meeting with the sector this month to discuss what they are looking for out of the European negotiations, and what more the government can do in the short and medium term to support the sector.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-10-14T09:41:18.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584203/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584203/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-15","Financial Services: Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what support he is providing to Fintech after the vote to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","46510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584204","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-14","<p>Climate change is not only a huge threat to our natural environment, but to our economic prosperity too. The private sector’s involvement is crucial if we are to be successful in reaching the ambitious targets agreed in Paris last year. The UK government and regulators are together at the forefront of engaging with the private sector to address this pressing issue:</p><ul><li><p>The Prudential Regulation Authority’s pioneering report on the impact of climate change on the UK insurance sector last year kick-started the global debate around climate-related financial risks.</p></li><li><p>The Bank of England is leading global efforts to develop the international framework for green finance as co-chair of the G20 Green Finance Study Group.</p></li><li><p>Governor Carney’s speech in Berlin last week stressed the importance of disclosure in addressing climate-related financial risks.</p></li></ul><p>The Financial Stability Board, chaired by Governor Carney, set up an industry-led Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures in late 2015, under the leadership of Michael Bloomberg. The Task Force is developing recommendations for voluntary, consistent, comparable, reliable and clear disclosures around climate-related financial risks for companies to provide information to investors, lenders, insurers, and other stakeholders. The Task Force published its initial report in April, and will publish a final report in early 2017. The Government looks forward to the publication of the Task Force’s report.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-10-14T09:38:59.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584204/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584204/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-15","Companies: Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to ensure that the Prudential Regulation Authority, the Bank of England and the Financial Conduct Authority are adequately ensuring that companies disclose the financial risk to their company associated with climate change.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","46575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584205","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-10","<p>The UK has a long and strong history in science, research and innovation, and a world-leading reputation, being ranked third in the Global Innovation Index in 2016. We have protected the science resource budget in real terms from its 2015/16 level of £4.7 billion for the rest of the parliament. Looking ahead, we want to ensure that the excellent work being done by our researchers, universities and innovative businesses continues. The Government has committed to underwrite payment of EU research funding for specific projects even when they continue beyond the UK’s departure from the EU.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-10-10T15:27:50.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584205/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584205/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-15","Technology: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to prevent the loss of technologies being developed in the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","46547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584206","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-14","<p>The UK does not have commercial contracts with other countries for arms and security related sales and services. Through bilateral government-to-government arrangements the UK works closely with its international partners and allies to support the development of their defence and security capabilities across a broad range of areas.</p><p>To produce the information would involve collecting data from all branches and services involved in international defence engagement activity which could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","46578","2016-10-14T12:14:55.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584206/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584206/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-15","Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what arms and security-related sales and services the UK is (a) contracted to provide and (b) planning to provide in (i) 2017, (ii) 2018 and (iii) 2019.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","46579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584207","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Government launched its consultation on tips, gratuities, service and cover charges to gain views on proposed actions towards tipping abuse. We are analysing submissions to this exercise and will announce further action in due course.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-10T15:05:21.23Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584207/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584207/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-15","Gratuities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he plans to publish his response to the results of his Department's consultation on tips, gratuities, service and cover charges that closed in June 2016.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","46587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584208","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-10","<p>I refer the hon. Member for Coventry South to the answer I gave on 19 September 2016 to the hon. Member for Kingston upon Hull North (Diana Johnson), UIN 46058.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-10-10T15:46:50.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584208/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584208/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-15","Arms Trade: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 15 September 2016 to Question 46072, what plans he has to replace the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","46675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584210","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-11","<p>The UK will remain a member of the EU until we formally exit, with all of the rights and obligations that membership entails. This means that the EU currently retains competence for most aspects of trade policy. We are, however, engaging with a broad range of international partners to best promote British trade, and to ensure that Britain becomes the global leader in free trade once we leave the EU.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-11T14:51:32.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584210/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584210/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-15","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether it is the Government's position that the UK can sign new trade deals before the UK has formally exited the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","46526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584211","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Secretary of State's oral statement on 5 September 2016 explained that his officials, supported by officials across Government, are carrying out a programme of sectoral and regulatory analysis, which will identify the key factors for British businesses and the labour force that will affect our negotiations with the EU. They are looking in detail at over 50 sectors and cross-cutting regulatory issues.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-10T16:06:32.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584211/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/584211/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-15","Economic Situation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether his Department is undertaking sectoral analyses of the effect of the UK leaving the EU on different sectors of the economy.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Williams","Ceredigion","Mr Mark Williams","46573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597709","Department for Education","false","2016-10-10","<p>It is essential that everyone, irrespective of background and upbringing, has the opportunity to get the skills and training they need to get on in life. Tech levels and certificates in schools, Traineeships, Apprenticeships, National Colleges, Institutes of Technology and proposed technical education reforms set out in the Skills Plan, present real opportunities for people of all ages to acquire the high quality skills and vocational or technical education that employers demand. Opportunity Areas will be at the forefront of my Department’s drive to increase opportunities for young people to develop the skills they need to succeed.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2016-10-10T16:12:06.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597709/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597709/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-09-15","Vocational Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to increase opportunities for young people to access skills and vocational education.","false","Biography information for Tom Pursglove","Corby","Tom Pursglove","906532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597710","Department for Education","false","2016-10-19","<p>Between 2012 and 2015, entries for Chinese GCSE in England increased by 34%.</p><p> </p><p>We introduced the Mandarin Excellence Programme this year for highly motivated pupils. It has started in 14 schools with more to follow over the next two years.</p><p> </p><p>The programme will result in at least 5,000 young people heading towards a high level of fluency in Mandarin by 2020.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-10-19T17:24:30.963Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597710/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597710/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-09-15","Mandarin Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps the Government is taking to increase the uptake of Mandarin.","false","Biography information for Caroline Ansell","Eastbourne","Caroline Ansell","906530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597711","Department for Education","false","2016-10-10","<p>The government is committed to a national funding formula that will deliver fairness to all parts of the country – rural and urban, north and south.</p><p>In the first stage of our consultation, we proposed including a sparsity factor which would help rural schools, as well as a lump sum factor which would help small schools everywhere.</p><p>We will both respond to the first consultation and launch the second stage consultation later in the autumn.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2016-10-10T16:11:45.63Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597711/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597711/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-09-15","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to reduce differences in urban and rural school funding.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Leigh","Gainsborough","Sir Edward Leigh","906535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597712","Department for Education","false","2016-10-19","<p>In our assessment the Higher Education and Research Bill will benefit all students. The Bill will deliver greater competition and choice, promoting all forms of learning, including for part time and mature students. However, we are not waiting for the Bill to take action. We will introduce part time maintenance loans in 2018 and from next year allow many more part time students to take a second degree in any science subject.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-10-19T17:25:39.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597712/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597712/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-09-15","Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of the provisions in the Higher Education and Research Bill on part-time and adult students.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","906538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597713","Department for Education","false","2016-10-10","<p>We are committed to providing the high-quality, affordable childcare that working families need.</p><p> </p><p>To enable the successful implementation of 30 hours of free childcare, we are investing £1billion of additional funding per year, including £300million per year to increase our national average funding rates.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-10-10T16:11:28.08Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597713/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/597713/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-09-15","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that funding is in place to implement its policy of 30 hours free childcare.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","906536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598498","Department of Health","false","2016-10-11","<p>In November 2015, the Department announced an ambitious campaign to halve the national rates of stillbirths, neonatal and maternal deaths and brain injuries occurring during or soon after birth, by 2030.</p><p>The Government has already invested in a capital fund for equipment to improve safety and training programmes for staff.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-10-11T14:33:08.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598498/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598498/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598498/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-15","Maternity Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to improve the safety of maternity care.","false","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak","906509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598499","Department of Health","false","2016-10-11","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is responsible for assessing whether providers are meeting the fundamental standards.</p><p>The Department monitors CQC’s financial and operational performance and risks at a general and strategic level through regular formal accountability meetings.</p><p>It does not assess CQC’s inspection or monitoring of specific providers.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-10-11T14:35:26.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598499/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598499/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-15","Care Quality Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the performance of the Care Quality Commission in monitoring GP surgeries; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","906507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598500","Department of Health","false","2016-10-11","<p>The Department is confident our world leading plan, <em>Childhood Obesity: A Plan for Action, </em>will make a real difference to obesity rates in this country.</p><p>The Government is currently consulting on the soft drinks industry levy and a broad sugar reduction programme has been launched.</p><p>The Department will continue to work with the National Health Service, local authorities and other partners as we move into the delivery phase of the plan.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-10-11T15:31:12.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598500/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598500/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-15","Obesity: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to implement his Department's plans on childhood obesity.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","906511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598501","Department of Health","false","2016-10-11","<p>An implementation plan for the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health was published in July which will see Mental Health spending increase by £1billion by 2020.</p>","South West Surrey","Mr Jeremy Hunt",,"2016-10-11T15:20:55.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598501/answer","Biography information for Mr Jeremy Hunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598501/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598501/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-15","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made on implementing the recommendations of the independent Mental Health Taskforce set out in the Five Year Forward View of February 2016.","false","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy","906506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598502","Department of Health","false","2016-10-11","<p>In 2004-05, there were 71,300 admitted patient finished consultant episodes at Kettering General Hospital NHS Foundation Trust, compared to 82,267 in 2009-10 and 90,659 in 2014-15.</p><p>The number of outpatient attendances has also risen, with 168,412 in 2004-05; 217,735 in 2009-10; and 274,614 in 2014-15.</p><p>In 2004-05, there were 68,650 Accident &amp; Emergency attendances, compared to 85,971 in 2009-10. This number fell in 2014-15 to 76,452 attendances.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-10-11T14:37:50.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598502/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598502/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/598502/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-15","Kettering General Hospital NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many patient episodes there were within the Kettering General Hospital NHS Trust in (a) 2005, (b) 2010 and (c) 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","906510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599868","Scotland Office","false","2016-10-12","<p>The British Business Bank currently facilitates around £300m of finance in Scotland. Around £10m of Start-Up Loans have been provided to over 2,000 Scottish businesses, and £290m is helping a further 2,000 businesses to grow through other Bank programmes. In 2015/16, Innovate UK committed to invest £58.3m in 291 innovation projects in Scotland.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-12T14:24:18.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599868/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/599868/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-09-15","Business: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what steps the Government is taking to support businesses in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Craig Tracey","North Warwickshire","Craig Tracey","906403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583065","Attorney General","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Government has committed to extending the scope of the Unduly Lenient Sentence scheme and is carefully considering its approach.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-10-10T13:31:25.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583065/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583065/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-09-14","Sentencing: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, whether there are plans to review the nature and type of offences that are capable of referral to the Court of Appeal on the grounds of leniency of sentencing.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","46370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583066","Attorney General","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) does not hold offences data prior to 2004-2005. Between the years 2004-2005 and 2015-2016, the CPS commenced prosecutions of 71 abortion related offences. However, it is not possible to disaggregate the data to report the occupation of the defendant, whether a medical professional or otherwise. This information could only be obtained by examining each of the CPS case files, which would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2016-10-10T13:31:34.7Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583066/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583066/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583066/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-09-14","Abortion: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, on how many occasions, and on what dates, the Crown Prosecution Service has decided to prosecute medical professionals for abortion-related offences since 1997-98.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","46456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583068","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-10","<p>There is no central Cabinet Office policy to reduce the overall Civil Service headcount in the current Parliament. Workforce planning is primarily the responsibility of each department to determine based on their individual operational and policy requirements. Each department has their own spending agreements with HM Treasury for this Parliament and are responsible for ensuring they have the right workforce and capability in place to deliver their commitments.</p><p>Earlier this year, departments published their Single Departmental Plans, setting out the key programmes of work required to deliver the Government’s Manifesto commitments. Departments have been developing plans to ensure they have the workforce required to deliver their Single Departmental Plans.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-10-10T09:20:22.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583068/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583068/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-14","Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether it is his Department's policy to reduce the overall civil service headcount in the current Parliament.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","46361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583069","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-10","<p>Workforce planning is primarily the responsibility of each department to determine based on their individual operational and policy requirements. Each department has their own spending agreement with HM Treasury for this Parliament and are responsible for ensuring they have the right workforce and capability in place to deliver their commitments.</p><p>Earlier this year, departments published their Single Departmental Plans, setting out the key programmes of work required to deliver the Government’s Manifesto commitments. Departments have been developing plans to ensure they have the workforce required to deliver their Single Departmental Plans.</p><p>The Civil Service constantly reviews its capabilities in order to deliver the Government’s agenda. Cabinet Office is working with all departments across the Civil Service to better understand their capacity and capability requirements over this Parliament following the decision to exit the EU, but it is too early to make a detailed assessment at this stage.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-10-10T09:14:50.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583069/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583069/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-14","Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether his Department has made an estimate of overall headcount and spending on civil servants across all Departments over the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","46360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583070","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-10","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-10-10T08:36:14.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583070/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583070/answer","PQ46354 V0.4.pdf","PQ46354 V0.4.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - People aged 80 and over","UKSA Letter to Member - People aged 80 and over","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583070/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-14","Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate has been made of the forecast change in the number of people aged 80 and over between 2015 and 2035.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","46354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583071","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-14","<p>Clean growth continues to be a priority for this Government. The full list of Interministerial Groups is currently being finalised.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-10-14T11:33:34.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583071/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583071/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-14","Clean Growth Ministerial Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Interministerial Group on Clean Growth plans to continue to meet.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","46366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583072","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-10","<p>All projects are ultimately the responsibility of individual government departments. However, with £400 billion in the Infrastructure Pipeline and £400 billion in the Major Projects Portfolio, the Cabinet Office has a central team, the Infrastructure Projects Authority (IPA), to support departments to deliver on time and within budget. The IPA provides expertise and practical help, a supportive environment to enable major projects to succeed, and manages an independent assurance process to ensure projects are delivered to time and within budget.</p><ul><li>IPA deploys expert commercial, financial and delivery support</li><li>IPA delivers independent high quality assurance and oversight</li><li>IPA develops standards, insights and tools, developing the project leadership and project finance professions</li><li>IPA delivers key finance schemes (PF2 &amp; guarantees) to enable key projects to proceed</li></ul><p>The IPA works with all partners in infrastructure and major projects - government departments, project teams, HMT, Cabinet Office, and the private sector - to do this. The IPA reports jointly to HMT and Cabinet Office Ministers.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-10-10T09:16:21.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583072/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583072/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-14","Government Departments: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps his Department takes to ensure that government projects are delivered on time and within budget.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","46376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583073","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-12","<p>Concentrix performance targets are outlined in the contract, which can be found at: <a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/85d1b730-5e4e-4be8-ae4c-3ac1f359afc7" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/85d1b730-5e4e-4be8-ae4c-3ac1f359afc7</a>. HM Revenue and Customs monitors Concentrix performance against the contractual performance indicators on a daily, weekly and monthly basis.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-12T16:13:52.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583073/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583073/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-14","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what targets the Government set for Concentrix on reviewing tax credit claims for each month in 2016 and 2017; and what targets the Government set in relation to tax credit claims being suspended.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","46382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583074","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Valuation Office Agency will consult with staff affected by the closure of the Preston office. Options will include working from an alternative location or working from home.</p><p> </p><p>The Agency is not looking to make redundancies and is committed to take every practical step to avoid job losses as a result of location changes.</p><p> </p><p>The Agency‘s transformation programme is changing the way the Agency works, focusing on a core network of offices and greater use of technology.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-12T10:30:07.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583074/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583074/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583074/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-14","Valuation Office Agency: Preston","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2016 to Question 45282, where staff who work at the Valuation Office Agency in Preston are planned to be deployed after the planned closure of that office; and how many staff at what cost at that office he plans  to make redundant after that closure.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","46380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583075","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-12","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not hold data broken down specifically by constituency areas.</p><p>HMRC is currently focussed on resolving the outstanding cases but will be preparing regional analysis, which will be available in due course.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-12T16:38:28.92Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583075/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583075/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583075/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-14","Welfare Tax Credits: Preston","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people in Preston constituency have their tax credits suspended.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","46381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583076","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-12","<p>Information about the assurance review process can be found within the Concentrix contract at: <a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/85d1b730-5e4e-4be8-ae4c-3ac1f359afc7" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/85d1b730-5e4e-4be8-ae4c-3ac1f359afc7</a></p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs monitors the financial accuracy of Concentrix decisions using the Quality Assurance Framework as part of the contract. This assures the delegation of Commissioner's Powers is discharged correctly by Concentrix to provide customers with the correct tax credit awards. This involves HMRC reviewing a monthly sample of 500 cases where a decision has been made by Concentrix to amend a tax credit award and assuring the accuracy level of those decisions. The assurance approach is set out within sections A38 and A39 of the contract.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-12T16:15:49.71Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583076/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583076/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583076/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-14","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what processes his Department has in place to review decisions made by Concentrix which resulted in the suspension of tax credits.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","46383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583077","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-14","<p>Between the commencement of the contract in November 2014 and the end of October 2015, the number of cases completed by Concentrix by risk type were as follows:</p><ul><li>107,677 childcare risk;</li><li>84,154 undeclared partner risk;</li><li>114,146 work and hours risk.</li></ul>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-14T09:32:47.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583077/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583077/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583077/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-14","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of cases of each risk type relating to error and fraud completed by SYNNEX-Concentrix under its contract with HM Revenue and Customs between May 2014 and October 2015.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","46384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583078","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-10","<p>This question has been passed on to the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA). The FCA will reply to directly to the Honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p><p> </p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","46390 ; 46392","2016-10-10T15:23:08.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583078/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583078/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583078/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-14","Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many high-cost, short-term credit firms have (a) been fully authorised and (b) had their authorisation denied by the Financial Conduct Authority.","false","Biography information for Yvonne Fovargue","Makerfield","Yvonne Fovargue","46388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583079","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-10","<p>Between 1 September 2015 and 31 August 2016, the average time taken to complete a tax credit undeclared partner investigation by HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) from the point at which they first write to the customer to closure, was 51.27 days. During the same period, Concentrix acting on behalf of HMRC took an average of 65.34 days.</p><p> </p><p>Where an alleged presence of an unreported adult occurs, claimants are given 30 days to contact HMRC or provide the relevant information. If after 30 days HMRC has had no contact, tax credit payments are either suspended or reduced. HMRC then gives the claimant a further 30 days to contact HMRC before making a decision on the household composition and tax credits award using all the available information.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-10T16:52:27.663Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583079/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583079/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583079/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-14","Welfare Tax Credits: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the average time taken was to complete an investigation into the alleged presence of an unreported adult in the household of a tax credit claimant in the past 12 months; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","46393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583080","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-10","<p>The information requested is not centrally held.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-10-10T15:20:48.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583080/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583080/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583080/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-14","Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the number of people employed in the UK by the high-cost, short-term credit sector.","false","Biography information for Yvonne Fovargue","Makerfield","Yvonne Fovargue","46389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583081","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-10","<p>This question has been passed on to the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA). The FCA will reply to directly to the Honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p><p> </p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","46388 ; 46392","2016-10-10T15:23:08.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583081/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583081/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583081/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-14","Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the change in the (a) volume and (b) value of high-cost, short-term loans has been since January 2015.","false","Biography information for Yvonne Fovargue","Makerfield","Yvonne Fovargue","46390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583082","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-10","<p>This question has been passed on to the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA). The FCA will reply to directly to the Honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p><p> </p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","46388 ; 46390","2016-10-10T15:23:08.54Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583082/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583082/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583082/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-14","Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many high-cost, short-term credit firms are operating with interim permissions.","false","Biography information for Yvonne Fovargue","Makerfield","Yvonne Fovargue","46392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583083","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-10","<ol><li><p>In this Parliament the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) has transferred £511 million of LIBOR fines to the Treasury. The Treasury is unaware of any potential future receipts, which are a matter for the FCA.</p></li></ol>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-10-10T15:49:44.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583083/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583083/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583083/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-14","LIBOR: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much his Department has (a) collected in Libor fines since May 2015 and (b) expects to collect in Libor fines in each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Ms Gisela Stuart","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Ms Gisela Stuart","46398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583084","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-10","<p>The UK Government has regular conversations with the Scottish Government about a wide range of economic policies, both at a ministerial and official level.</p><p> </p><p>The Chief Secretary to the Treasury met with the Cabinet Secretary for Finance and the Constitution, Derek Mackay MSP, on 19 September and will continue to work with the Scottish Government to implement the Scotland Act and the Scottish Government’s fiscal framework.</p><p> </p><p>From April 2017, it will be for the Scottish Parliament to set the income tax rates and thresholds that will apply to Scottish taxpayers’ non-savings, non-dividend income, such as that from employment and pensions.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-10T15:31:25.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583084/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583084/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583084/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-14","Income Tax: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with HM Revenue and Customs and Ministers of the Scottish Government on changes to the rates and bands of income tax in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","46421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583085","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-12","<p>This information is not held in the form requested. An amended award could be due to a number or reasons and without retrospectively looking at each award individually, HM Revenue and Customs would not be able to identify how many amendments were made in error. Undertaking an assurance exercise of this size could only be done at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-12T16:17:37.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583085/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583085/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583085/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-14","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many amendments to tax credit awards Concentrix have made due to error on behalf of (a) Concentrix and (b) since the beginning of the contract between Concentrix and HM Revenue and Customs.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","46444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583086","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-14","<p>The process to measure performance as described in the question was introduced as part of the contract variation signed on 13 October 2015. The information is therefore not available for the period requested.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-14T09:27:55.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583086/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583086/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583086/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-14","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2016 to Question 44656, how many (a) amber, (b) amber green, (c) red and (d) black performance failures there were between May 2014 and October 2015 in respect of benefits and credits error and fraud.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","46445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583088","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-10","<p>Information about the use of profiling techniques can be found within the Concentrix contract at Annex A10.2 and A22.1: <a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/85d1b730-5e4e-4be8-ae4c-3ac1f359afc7" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/85d1b730-5e4e-4be8-ae4c-3ac1f359afc7</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-10T15:25:43.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583088/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583088/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583088/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-14","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to section A8.1 of the Benefits and Credits, Error and Fraud Adding Capacity 444 contract between SYNNEX-Concentrix UK Limited and HM Revenue and Customs, what the profiling techniques are that are used to identify non-compliance.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","46422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583089","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-10","<p>On 16<sup>th</sup> September I responded to a number of parliamentary questions on the number of mandatory reconsiderations requested by tax credit claimants this year.</p><p> </p><p>Where a discrepancy is detected, claimants are given 30 days to contact HMRC or provide the relevant information. If after 30 days HMRC has had no contact, tax credit payments are either suspended or reduced. HMRC then gives the claimant a further 30 days to contact HMRC before making a decision on the tax credits award using all the available information.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-10T16:54:47.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583089/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583089/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583089/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-14","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of people who have had their tax credits stopped and subsequently reinstated by Concentrix in each of the last 12 months; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","46494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583090","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-14","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) has, to date, spent circa £30 million with Concentrix for service delivery under the contract. HMRC, under appropriate procurement transparency mandates, published anticipated spend details on Contracts Finder of between £55-75 million pounds at the start of the contract.</p><p> </p><p>Final spend with the supplier will be dictated by contractual considerations around delivery of specific service campaigns. Such considerations are commercially sensitive at this time and cannot, in this instance, be disclosed.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-14T09:29:40.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583090/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583090/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583090/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-14","Treasury: Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the total value of the contract between his Department and Concentrix; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","46490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583091","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-11","<p>Our rich cultural heritage makes the UK a great place to live and attracts millions of visitors each year. In the White Paper we committed to ensuring we continue to celebrate our heritage and make sure we can pass on something even more inspirational to future generations.</p><p> </p><p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. During this period, we will continue to participate in EU initiatives, and the European Year of Cultural Heritage is a potential opportunity to showcase UK heritage. We will continue to work with the heritage sector to determine the nature of our involvement.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-10-11T14:31:57.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583091/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583091/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583091/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-14","Cultural Heritage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the potential benefits of the UK taking part in the European Year of Cultural Heritage proposed for 2018 by the European Commission for her Department's objectives set out in the Culture White Paper, published in March 2016 ; what assessment she has made of the implications of the outcome of the EU referendum on UK participation in that event; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","46350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583092","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-11","<p>I have regular meetings with the Leagues, and have discussed the Owners and Directors Test (formerly Fit and Proper Persons Test) with them. The test exists to protect clubs from individuals who fall within the disqualifying criteria, and I am pleased that The Football Association, The Premier League and the English Football League have committed to keeping it under constant review so that it is achieving its intended purpose. This commitment is set out in the report by the Government's Expert Working Group on Supporter Ownership and Engagement published earlier this year.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-10-11T14:33:11.56Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583092/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583092/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583092/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-14","Football","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what representations she has made to the Football League and the Premier League on whether the Fit and Proper Person Test they use is appropriate and effective; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","46442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583093","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-11","<p>Any concerns to my Department (DCMS) regarding football's rules and regulations, including the application of the Owners and Directors Test (formerly Fit and Proper Persons Test) are referred to the Football Association or Leagues. It is however worth noting that as well as a commitment to keep the Test under constant review, the Football Authorities have also said they will meet with supporter representative groups to listen to any concerns they have over current or prospective owners. The intention is set out in the Government Expert Work Group's report on Football Supporter Ownership and Engagement.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-10-11T14:29:28.72Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583093/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583093/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583093/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-14","Football","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what representations she has received from football supporters clubs in England and Wales on whether the Fit and Proper Person Test used by the Football League and Premier League is appropriate and effective; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","46443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583094","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-10","<p>Tourism is a devolved matter but a number of policy levers - from aviation connectivity to aspects of the regulatory framework and immigration - are reserved. Through the recently published Tourism Action Plan, this Government is working to ensure the benefits of growth in the tourism industry can be felt across the whole of the UK.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-10-10T10:36:43.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583094/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583094/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583094/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-14","Tourism: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to promote tourism in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","46429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583095","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-10","<p>As set out in the 2015 Strategic Defence and Security Review (SDSR), we are working in partnership with the UK defence industry and our closest allies to understand and develop the technologies that will be required for future combat air systems (FCAS). No decisions have yet been made as to what this system will consist of, nor the platforms and capabilities that it will include. We are focussing now on developing the core technologies that any such system will require. To do this we have developed and are implementing the FCAS technology initiative. This programme includes the development of an advanced unmanned combat air system (UCAS) demonstrator in partnership with France, bilateral projects with the United States (US) to mature other key technologies and a national programme to maintain the UK's position as a global leader in the combat air sector.</p><p>In Amiens in March 2016 we agreed to transition to the next phase of the UK/France UCAS programme in 2017 and to develop the full-scale demonstrators by 2025. In addition to the current projects we are in discussions with the US and other allies to understand areas of mutual interest for further collaborative work.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-10-10T14:47:35.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583095/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583095/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583095/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-14","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what progress has been made on the Future Combat Air System.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","46409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583096","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-10","<table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2" rowspan="5"><p> </p></td><td colspan="6" rowspan="5"><p>I refer my right hon. Friend to the answer given by the then Minister for Defence Procurement (Philip Dunne) to the hon. Member for Dunfermline and West Fife (Douglas Chapman) on 13 June 2016 to Question 40031.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-10-10T14:48:10.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583096/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583096/answer","Hansard Extract 13 June 2016 40031.docx","Hansard Extract 13 June 2016 40031.docx","HMS Lancaster","HMS Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583096/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-14","HMS Lancaster","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the state of readiness is of HMS Lancaster; and when HMS Lancaster will return to operations.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","46411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583097","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Strategic Defence and Security Review of 2015 announced the out of service date for the Typhoon fleet would be extended to 2040. The Ministry of Defence will consider options to replace the capability closer to that date but so far no decision has been made.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-10-12T15:17:58.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583097/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583097/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583097/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-14","European Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans his Department has for developing for a crewed successor to Typhoon.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","46438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583098","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Ministry of Defence is not aware of any credible evidence to date of civilian casualties as a result of UK airstrikes over Syria and Iraq.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-10-12T15:18:33.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583098/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583098/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583098/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-14","Syria: Guided Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many civilian casualties have resulted from the 26 brimstone missiles dropped by UK aircraft in Syria in 2016 to date.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","46434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583099","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-10","<table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2" rowspan="5"><p> </p></td><td colspan="6" rowspan="5"><p>Of the 297 Regular and Reserve personnel currently serving with 77th Brigade, 11 (4%) personnel are from the Royal Navy, 276 (93%) are from the Army and 10 (3%) are from the Royal Air Force. This includes 18 Special Reserve Officers with niche skills, most of whom do not have previous military service. The remainder of the Regular and Reserve personnel have transferred to 77th Brigade from other units.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-10-10T14:45:37.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583099/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583099/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583099/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-14","Armed Forces: Information Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many and what proportion of military personnel serving in the 77th Brigade served in the (a) Army, (b) Royal Navy and (c) Royal Air Force before joining that unit; and how many such personnel have not previously served in any branch of the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","46420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583100","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-10","<p>The majority of personnel joining 77th Brigade transfer from other Regular or Reserve units and are therefore not recruits. The exception to this is Specialist Reserve Officers (SROs), who are recruited as civilians with niche skills. 44 SROs have been selected since 1 January 2015 of which 18 have completed the recruitment process and are currently on strength.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-10-10T14:46:04.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583100/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583100/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583100/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-14","Armed Forces: Information Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many recruits have joined the 77th Brigade as (a) regular and (b) reserve personnel since the formation of that unit in 2015.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","46419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583101","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-12","<p>The UK supported US efforts to reach agreement with Russia to reinstate a cessation of hostilities in Syria and will continue to work for the restoration of a credible cessation of Hostilities. The UK was not, however, a party to the US-Russia arrangement which was a purely bilateral one. While the UK would have considered seriously any requests received, we were not asked for either assistance or reconnaissance intelligence for its implementation.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","46449 ; 46450","2016-10-12T15:17:11.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583101/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583101/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583101/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-14","Islamic State: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the UK plans to provide any assistance or reconnaissance intelligence for airstrikes against Daesh conducted as part of the Syrian Counter Terror agreement made by the US and Russia on 9 September 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","46448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583102","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-12","<p>The UK supported US efforts to reach agreement with Russia to reinstate a cessation of hostilities in Syria and will continue to work for the restoration of a credible cessation of Hostilities. The UK was not, however, a party to the US-Russia arrangement which was a purely bilateral one. While the UK would have considered seriously any requests received, we were not asked for either assistance or reconnaissance intelligence for its implementation.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","46448 ; 46450","2016-10-12T15:17:11.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583102/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583102/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583102/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-14","Jabhat Fateh al-Sham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the UK plans to provide any assistance or reconnaissance intelligence for airstrikes against Jabhat al-Nusra conducted as part of the Syrian Counter Terror agreement made by the US and Russia on 9 September 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","46449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583103","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-12","<p>The UK supported US efforts to reach agreement with Russia to reinstate a cessation of hostilities in Syria and will continue to work for the restoration of a credible cessation of Hostilities. The UK was not, however, a party to the US-Russia arrangement which was a purely bilateral one. While the UK would have considered seriously any requests received, we were not asked for either assistance or reconnaissance intelligence for its implementation.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","46448 ; 46449","2016-10-12T15:17:11.28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583103/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583103/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583103/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-14","Middle East: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the UK is a party to the Syrian Counter Terror Agreement made by the US and Russia on 9 September 2016; whether the UK plans to provide any assistance or reconnaissance intelligence for actions taken under that agreement; and whether British forces' operations in Iraq and Syria will be affected by that agreement.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","46450"
