"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583179","Department of Health","false","2016-10-11","<p>The National Stroke Strategy remains valid and implementation of it continues. There are, therefore, no current plans to renew the national stroke strategy. Action is being taken to ensure the progress made on stroke continues. This includes;</p><p>- publication of the Cardiovascular Disease (CVD) Outcomes Strategy in 2013, which includes many stroke specific strategic ambitions;</p><p>- a CVD expert forum, hosted by NHS England, to coordinate delivery of the work which was initiated in the CVD Outcomes Strategy; and</p><p>- NHS England’s National Clinical Director for stroke working with the Strategic Clinical Networks, Urgent and Emergency Care Networks, clinical commissioning groups, Sustainability and Transformation Plans, voluntary agencies and individual providers to support better commissioning and provision of stroke care.</p><p>More generally, the NHS Five Year Forward View recognises that quality of care, including stroke care, can be variable and that patients’ needs are changing and new treatment options are emerging. The Five Year Forward View sets out high level objectives to address these issues.</p><p>There has been no formal evaluation of the National Stroke Strategy. However there is a continuous evaluation of the quality of stroke care via the Sentinel Stroke National Audit Programme (SSNAP). This measures most of the key indicators defined as important in the strategy and findings are available on the SSNAP website:</p><p><a href="https://www.strokeaudit.org/" target="_blank">https://www.strokeaudit.org/</a></p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","46461","2016-10-11T09:52:38.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583179/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583179/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583179/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-14","Strokes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans his Department has for replacing or renewing the National Stroke Strategy when it expires in 2017.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","46460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583180","Department of Health","false","2016-10-11","<p>The National Stroke Strategy remains valid and implementation of it continues. There are, therefore, no current plans to renew the national stroke strategy. Action is being taken to ensure the progress made on stroke continues. This includes;</p><p>- publication of the Cardiovascular Disease (CVD) Outcomes Strategy in 2013, which includes many stroke specific strategic ambitions;</p><p>- a CVD expert forum, hosted by NHS England, to coordinate delivery of the work which was initiated in the CVD Outcomes Strategy; and</p><p>- NHS England’s National Clinical Director for stroke working with the Strategic Clinical Networks, Urgent and Emergency Care Networks, clinical commissioning groups, Sustainability and Transformation Plans, voluntary agencies and individual providers to support better commissioning and provision of stroke care.</p><p>More generally, the NHS Five Year Forward View recognises that quality of care, including stroke care, can be variable and that patients’ needs are changing and new treatment options are emerging. The Five Year Forward View sets out high level objectives to address these issues.</p><p>There has been no formal evaluation of the National Stroke Strategy. However there is a continuous evaluation of the quality of stroke care via the Sentinel Stroke National Audit Programme (SSNAP). This measures most of the key indicators defined as important in the strategy and findings are available on the SSNAP website:</p><p><a href="https://www.strokeaudit.org/" target="_blank">https://www.strokeaudit.org/</a></p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","46460","2016-10-11T09:52:38.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583180/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583180/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583180/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-14","Strokes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what mechanisms his Department has for measuring the effectiveness of the National Stroke Strategy; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","46461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583182","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-14","<p>​As the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson), said to the UN Security Council on 21 September, we are very concerned about the appalling crimes committed in Iraq and Syria and are committed to bringing to justice those responsible for alleged acts of genocide, crimes against humanity and war crimes. There have not been any prosecutions to date for such crimes in British courts. Most of the prosecutions of those returning to the UK from Iraq or Syria have been for terrorism-related offences. UK nationals can be prosecuted for genocide, crimes against humanity and war crimes in domestic courts; but the practical difficulties involved in investigating crimes that have taken place abroad and apprehending suspects outside the jurisdiction will need to be considered by police and prosecutors on a case-by-case basis.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-10-14T11:51:27.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583182/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583182/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583182/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-14","Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment the Government has made of the practicability of prosecuting potential acts of genocide, crimes against humanity and war crimes committed in Syria and Iraq by radicalised UK citizens in British courts.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","46455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583184","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-14","<p>As the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend, the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson MP), said to the UN Security Council on 21 September, we are working with our partners in the international community to do everything we can to support the gathering of evidence which could be used by courts to bring Daesh to justice. On 19 September, the Foreign Secretary launched at the UN General Assembly an international campaign to bring Daesh to justice. As a state party to the International Criminal Court (ICC) Rome Statute and strong supporter of the ICC, the UK has regular discussions with the court on a range of issues. Any decision to refer to the ICC must be made on the basis of what will be the most effective means to bring perpetrators of atrocities and those who have assisted them to justice. In her press statement of 8 April 2015, the ICC Prosecutor set out some of the complicated issues involved in the ICC investigating Daesh, including foreign fighters who are nationals of from ICC states parties. When efforts were made to refer the situation in Syria to the ICC in 2014, it was vetoed by Russia and China.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-10-14T11:55:51.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583184/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583184/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583184/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-14","British Nationals Abroad: Middle East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Government has (a) had discussions with and (b) made referrals to the International Criminal Court on investigating possible (i) acts of genocide, (ii) war crimes and (iii) crimes against humanity in Syria and Iraq by radicalised UK citizens.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","46373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583185","Home Office","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Home Office publishes quarterly figures on asylum applications and initial decisions (including grants) within the Immigration Statistics release.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-10T13:11:36.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583185/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583185/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583185/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-14","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people her Department has granted asylum to in each year from 2010 to 2016.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","46378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583186","Home Office","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Government is fully committed to the efficient and timely operation of the Dublin Regulation and we are working closely with EU partners, including the Greek authorities, to identify, assess and transfer those with family connections to the UK under the Dublin family reunion process.</p><p>We have seconded an expert to Greece to coordinate efforts on transferring unaccompanied children to the UK. We are following due process to ensure that any transfer is in their best interests and is lawful under EU legislation.</p><p>More broadly, the UK has offered 75 expert personnel to help with the processing and administration of migrants in reception centres, act as interpreters, provide medical support and bolster our existing team assisting the Commission to ensure effective and efficient coordination.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-12T11:23:37.71Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583186/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583186/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583186/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-14","Asylum: Greece","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 7 September 2016 to Question 43711, if she will take steps to increase the number of transfers to the UK of refugees in camps in Greece with family connections in the UK.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","46402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583187","Home Office","false","2016-10-10","<p>There are no current plans to change the law to enable councils in England to operate combined registration districts. Under existing legislation some local authorities undertake joint working initiatives to offer improved service options, which have proved successful.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-10T13:06:30.04Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583187/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583187/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583187/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-14","Registration of Births, Deaths, Marriages and Civil Partnerships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make it the policy of the Government to enable councils in England to operate combined registration districts.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","46428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583188","Home Office","false","2016-10-10","<p>We intend to resettle up to 20,000 Syrians in need of protection and up to 3,000 vulnerable persons from the Middle East and North African region in the UK over the lifetime of this Parliament.</p><p>We will continue to work closely with the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) to identify appropriate cases, prioritising the most vulnerable. The numbers resettled in a particular period will depend on a range of factors including the flow of referrals from UNHCR in the field and the availability of suitable accommodation and care packages in the UK.</p><p>We will manage the flows based on need and in support of the wellbeing of the people and communities involved, rather than rushing to meet arbitrary targets. However, we are clear that we want to help as many people as we can as quickly as possible.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-10T13:11:22.353Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583188/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583188/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583188/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-14","Refugees: Middle East and North Africa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) Syrian refugees and (b) vulnerable persons from the Middle East and North African region the UK plans to resettle in the UK over each of the next four years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","46417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583189","Home Office","false","2016-10-10","<p>I want to be clear that an assault of any kind on a police officer or Police Community Support Officer is wholly unacceptable. The choice of which is the most appropriate offence to charge an offender with is one that the Crown Prosecution Service must take.</p><p>Sentencing guidelines already provide for assault of a police officer to be treated more severely in appropriate cases. The courts need to be able to take into account all the circumstances of each case.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-10-10T13:12:11.94Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583189/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583189/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583189/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-14","Police: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect on police safety of the distinction between the offences of assault on a police officer or police community support officer and resisting arrest.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","46387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583190","Home Office","false","2016-10-10","<p>Details of core Government funding to Police and Crime Commissioners (and previously Police Authorities) are published annually in the Police Grant Report. These can be found at https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-finance Figures for 2010-11 to 2016-17 are shown below for information. Police and Crime Commissioners are required to publish annual group accounts showing the budget and expenditure for their respective police forces and their own offices, including precept and other local income. For West Midlands Police, these are available at http://www.westmidlands-pcc.gov.uk/transparency/budgetary-and-financial-information/statements-of-accounts</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Core Government funding (£)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>504,297,082</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>497,784,836</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>464,421,955</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>472,809,895</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>456,919,964</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>433,573,284</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>431,099,809</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Note: Some specific grants have been rolled into core Government funding over this period, including in 2012/13, the Neighbourhood Policing Fund and in 2014/15, the Community Safety Fund. This affects comparison between the figures over the period. Additionally, core funding previously paid by DCLG became part of Home Office core funding in 2013/14. These figures are included in all years to aid comparison.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-10-10T13:40:26.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583190/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583190/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583190/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-14","West Midlands Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the total budget was for West Midlands police force in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","46436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583191","Home Office","false","2016-10-10","<p>Action Fraud is the national reporting point for fraud and financially-motivated cyber crime. We have seen significant improvement in performance; official figures show reports of fraud have trebled since Action Fraud was rolled out nationally, addressing the concern that fraud was an under-reported crime type.</p><p>Since it's launch the Government has been building the capability of police forces, GCHQ and the NCA to respond to online cyber crime. Over the last year, Action Fraud has introduced an improved system which keeps victims informed of the progress of their case. The number of disseminations to local forces has also increased.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-10-10T09:05:18.743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583191/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583191/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583191/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-14","Action Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment she has made of the effectiveness of Action Fraud.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bridgen","North West Leicestershire","Andrew Bridgen","46433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583192","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-10","<p>DFID has a zero tolerance approach to fraud and has a wide range of robust measures and controls in place to protect UK aid and ensure we maximise value for money. My department works in challenging areas and operates a comprehensive risk management framework which assesses and responds to the risk of fraud at every stage of the project cycle. The Counter Fraud Section responds firmly to any allegation of fraud recovering funds wherever possible. We expect our partners to account for losses from their own funds to minimise the impact on UK taxpayers and the recipients of aid.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-10T15:51:28.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583192/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583192/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583192/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-14","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to her article in the Daily Mail, entitled Too much of your money is simply stolen or squandered, published on 13 September 2016, in what areas of her Department's spending funding is being stolen or wasted.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","46379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583193","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-10","<p>UK aid is supporting Britain’s interests through building a safer more prosperous world and helping countries achieve a timely sustainable exit from poverty. It is not possible to accurately predict which countries will require aid in those timeframes, but assessments of the likely trajectory of poverty in a country informs how we allocate resources. Programmes are largely focused on countries where extreme poverty currently affects a significant proportion of the population; is projected to persist over the medium term; where DFID has a comparative advantage; and, where the country itself is unable to finance their own development needs.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-10T15:53:28.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583193/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583193/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583193/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-14","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what forecast she has made of which countries in receipt of UK aid will no longer require UK aid in (a) five, (b) 10 and (c) 15 years.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","46336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583194","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-10","<p>My department’s assessment is that aid delivered by road, by trusted humanitarian partners who can ensure it gets to those who need it most, remains the best way of getting help to affected populations. The use of air drops to deliver aid is high risk and should only be considered as a last resort when all other means have failed, and if it is an effective way of getting humanitarian supplies to people. Air drops require certain conditions to be met for successful delivery that are difficult to meet in most of Syria; ideally including clear drop zones, safe air space and access for the intended recipients, and co-ordination with authorities on the ground to oversee distribution.</p><p>We therefore continue to deliver the majority of our supplies by road, although our partners have made occasional air-drops in the past.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-10T16:12:17.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583194/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583194/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583194/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-14","Syria: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 13 June 2016 to Question 40083, what recent assessment her Department made of the feasibility of air drops of humanitarian aid in Syria.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","46489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583196","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-10","<p>The UK Government is playing a leading role in improving energy access in developing countries. DFID has a range of programmes which are working with developing countries to ensure renewable energy markets work effectively as well as supporting energy businesses to grow, and providing consumers with access to funding to buy solar goods. For example, our Energy Access Ventures programme is investing in off-grid electric and we are delivering green mini-grid solutions across Africa.</p><p>Through the UK Government’s Energy Africa campaign we are working with solar firms to help them access the finance they need to expand their businesses, create jobs and help reach millions of people in Africa without electricity access.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-10-10T15:59:14.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583196/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583196/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583196/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-14","Developing Countries: Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans she has to increase investment in decentralised renewable energy in developing countries.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","46493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583197","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-11","<p>Victims deserve the best possible support to help them cope with what they have been through and recover as much as possible. We have protected the victims' budget and given PCCs the flexibility to decide which services are needed in their local area. Under the revised Victims' Code, victims of all criminal offences are now entitled to support from a wide range of organisations. But we know there is more to do, which is why we have committed to introduce measures to increase further the rights of victims. It is important that we take the time to get this right and we will announce our plans in due course.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-10-11T14:37:33.903Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583197/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583197/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583197/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-14","Crime: Victims","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether she plans to publish a green paper on the case for a victims' law for consultation during this parliamentary session.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","46465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583198","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-10","<p>Marine Sergeant Blackman’s application to the Criminal Cases Review Commission is being treated as a Priority 1 case, the highest level of priority available.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-10-10T14:00:45.103Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583198/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583198/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583198/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-14","Alexander Blackman","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will make representations to the Criminal Cases Review Commission on expediting its investigations into the case of former Marine Sergeant Alexander Blackman.","false","Biography information for Richard Drax","South Dorset","Richard Drax","46375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583199","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-12","<p>The representation status of unsuccessful applicants for legal aid is not centrally recorded. The Government is absolutely clear that victims of domestic violence must have access to the help they need, including access to legal aid. The operation of, and expenditure on, the legal aid scheme is continually monitored by the Ministry of Justice and the Legal Aid Agency. Since the reforms were introduced thousands of people have applied for legal aid where domestic violence is involved and the majority have been granted it. Since the LASPO Act was introduced we have twice made changes so it is easier for people to get the evidence they need to claim legal aid.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-10-12T12:16:41.36Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583199/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583199/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583199/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-14","Administration of Justice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 7 September 2016 to Question 44521, what information her Department holds on how many (a) petitioners and (b) respondents who were ineligible for legal aid were unable to afford legal representation in applications to the family court for child contact or residence applications in 2015; how many such petitioners and respondents alleged that they were victims of domestic violence from the other party; and whether her Department has undertaken monitoring of the effect of a lack of legal representation on those victims and their children.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","46401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583200","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-10","<p>Whilst the British Government did not raise the subject of Rohingya refugees at the UN Summit on Refugees on 19 September 2016, we remain keen to play our part in helping refugees globally. We are deeply concerned about the ongoing persecution of the Rohingya and have repeatedly raised our concerns with the Burmese Government at the highest levels. The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson), discussed the Rohingya with State Counsellor Aung San Suu Kyi during her visit to the UK in September and I raised the issue in my intervention at the UN Secretary General’s Partnership Group during my visit to the UN General Assembly in September.</p><p>The British Government is one of the largest bilateral donors to Rakhine providing over £18 million in humanitarian assistance since the intercommunal violence of 2012. Across the border in south east Bangladesh, a total of 82,000 people have benefitted from UK funded humanitarian programmes. Since 2014, the British Government has provided nearly £8 million to address the humanitarian suffering of Rohingya refugees and the vulnerable Bangladeshi communities that host them.</p><p>We are encouraged to see the new Burmese Government has started to take real steps to try to defuse tensions in Rakhine while making progress for the Rohingya, including through the recently announced Rakhine Commission led by former UN Secretary General Kofi Annan, formation of a cross-Government Rakhine committee and re-starting the citizenship verification exercise. On 25 August I issued a statement welcoming the establishment of the Rakhine Commission, and on 14 September I spoke by phone with Mr Annan to convey the UK’s strong support for his appointment and mandate.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-10-10T14:31:11.28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583200/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583200/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583200/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-14","Rohingya: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what plans he has to raise the situation of Rohingya refugees at the UN Summit on Refugees on 19 September 2016.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","46399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583203","Home Office","false","2016-10-10","<p>Anti-Slavery Day on 18 October is an important opportunity to continue to raise awareness of this appalling crime. We have made good progress in tackling it, but there is more to do.</p><p>A range of events will mark the day and the Government will announce its plans in due course.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-10-10T13:12:32.877Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583203/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583203/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-14","Anti-slavery Day","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to mark Anti-Slavery Day 2016; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lord Garnier","Harborough","Sir Edward Garnier","46431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583204","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Department has recently commissioned the Behavioural Insights Team to deliver a programme of workshops on the use of behavioural insights research in policy making, including rail passenger experience. In addition, the Department is currently exploring a range of behavioural insight approaches as part of its wider programme of rail research.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-10T11:19:33.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583204/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583204/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-14","Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will commission the Behavioural Insights Team to conduct research on efficiency and passenger journeys in the rail sector.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","46473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583205","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-11","<p>The Government is considering the impacts of the decision to leave the European Union, including future arrangements for existing legislation. Until the UK leaves, EU law continues to apply, so we continue to comply with the existing directives and regulations, such as the common rules on compensation and assistance under Regulation (EC) 261/2004.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-11T08:43:53.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583205/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583205/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-14","Aviation: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department plans to replace EU Regulation EC 261/2004 on compensation and assistance to airline passengers with a similar UK compensation system after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","46400"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583206","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-10","<p>Safety at public beaches is generally the responsibility of the local authority, who carry out risk assessments to determine appropriate safety measures.</p><p> </p><p>Gwynedd Council have information guides about beach and harbour safety on their website.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-10T15:32:36.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583206/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583206/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-14","Beaches: Gwynedd","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which authority is responsible  for the safety of (a) beach users and (b) swimmers at beaches in Gwynedd.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","46397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583207","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-10","<p>From 2009-10 to 2015-16, the Government spent £1.4bn on the HS2 programme. The total payroll costs for HS2 Ltd permanent staff for the same period were £94.6m, out of which £113.5k was spent on performance related pay.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-10T14:33:34.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583207/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583207/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-14","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of total spending on High Speed 2 has been on (a) wages and (b) performance bonuses.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","46394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583208","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Department for Transport receives a wide variety of representations from a diverse range of stakeholders in relation to private hire vehicle licensing, including child sexual exploitation.</p><p> </p><p>Alongside the Government’s commitment to eradicating child sexual abuse, these representations have assisted us in taking action such as introducing statutory Best Practice Guidance for taxi and private hire vehicle licensing in relation to safeguarding.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-10T12:18:43.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583208/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583208/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-14","Taxis: Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent representations he has received on child sexual exploitation and the licensing of private hire vehicles.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","46363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583210","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Department for Transport does not hold data on the number of child sexual exploitation prosecutions related to private hire vehicles. Such information should be sought from the Police.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-10T12:15:53.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583210/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583210/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-14","Taxis: Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many child sexual exploitation issues prosecutions have been brought in relation to private hire vehicles in each year since 2000.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","46364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583211","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) takes the protection of the data it holds very seriously and has measures in place to protect it. These measures vary depending on the service used and the sensitivity of the data provided.</p><p> </p><p>All DVLA’s data release services are subject to a formal assessment before they are made available for use. This ensures that there are adequate policies as well as procedural and technical controls in place to protect the data. Privacy Impact Assessments are also completed to identify and address any privacy risks associated with the service and ensure that personal data is processed in compliance with the law.</p><p> </p><p>An audit carried out earlier this year by the Information Commissioner’s Office confirmed that the DVLA’s procedures offer high assurance that processes are in place to mitigate the risks of non-compliance with the Data Protection Act.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-10T15:53:12.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583211/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583211/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-14","Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department has taken to ensure that the DVLA does not give out motorists' data to organisations which will misuse it.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","46374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583212","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-11","<p>The Infrastructure and Projects Authority (IPA) provides expertise, practical help and independent assurance of major projects, working with all partners in infrastructure and major projects (government departments, project teams, HMT, Cabinet Office, and the private sector). The remit of the IPA does not include providing formal approval and as such departments do not submit business cases to the IPA for approval.</p><p> </p><p>The IPA publish an annual comprehensive forward-looking assessment of the current and planned investment in UK economic infrastructure across both the public and private sectors (The National Infrastructure Pipeline). This document contains financial information of the level of public and private infrastructure investment broken down by region currently in development and planned to 2021 and beyond. The Spring 2016 update can be found at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-infrastructure-pipeline-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-infrastructure-pipeline-2016</a>.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-11T13:03:52.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583212/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583212/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-14","Transport: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many business cases for infrastructure projects submitted in previous years by his Department were accepted in the 2015-16 financial year in each region; and what the (a) value was of (i) public and (ii) private funds allocated to those projects in total in each region and (b) average length of time taken was for the Department to accept those cases.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","46372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583213","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-10","<p>The UK government has agreed in principle to support the air route between City of Derry Airport and London though a Public Service Obligation. It is now for Derry City &amp; Strabane District Council take forward the tender process to identify an airline to operate the route.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-10T15:21:30.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583213/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583213/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-14","Stansted Airport: Londonderry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of offering Public Service Obligation Route status to the Londonderry to Stansted Airport service.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","46357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583214","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-10","<p>Simon Kirby has built a high calibre team and leaves HS2 Ltd in excellent shape. Sir David Higgins remains as chair and a new CEO will be appointed as soon as possible. The 2026 target date for opening phase one of HS2 is not affected.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-10T10:51:15.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583214/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583214/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-14","High Speed Two: Resignations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of Simon Kirby's resignation from HS2 Ltd on achieving the 2026 target date for opening phase one of High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","46358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583215","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Secretary of State last met with Simon Kirby on 20 July 2016. He was made aware of Simon Kirby’s resignation as CEO of HS2 Ltd on the afternoon of Friday 9 September 2016.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-10T10:54:27.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583215/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583215/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-14","High Speed Two","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he last met Simon Kirby, Chief Executive of HS2 Ltd; and when he was made aware of Mr Kirby's decision to resign as Chief Executive of that company.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","46359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583216","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-10","<p>We oppose any measure that imposes unreasonable costs on British motorists, home owners and businesses. We are pleased to have achieved positive progress; the Commission has agreed in principle that the Motor Insurance Directive should be amended. They set out their high level proposals in an Inception Impact Assessment in June.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State will consult in due course on whether or not to make changes to how the Motor Insurance Directive is implemented in domestic law.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","46349","2016-10-10T13:37:05.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583216/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583216/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-14","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential implications for its policies of the European Court of Justice ruling of September 2014, Damijan Vnuk v Zavarovalnica Triglav C-162/13, on the requirement for all motorised vehicles used off-road to be insured.","false","Biography information for Sammy Wilson","East Antrim","Sammy Wilson","46348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583217","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-10","<p>We oppose any measure that imposes unreasonable costs on British motorists, home owners and businesses. We are pleased to have achieved positive progress; the Commission has agreed in principle that the Motor Insurance Directive should be amended. They set out their high level proposals in an Inception Impact Assessment in June.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State will consult in due course on whether or not to make changes to how the Motor Insurance Directive is implemented in domestic law.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","46348","2016-10-10T13:37:05.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583217/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583217/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-14","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans his Department has made to bring forward legislative proposals to implement the ruling of the European Court of Justice of September 2014, Damijan Vnuk v Zavarovalnica Triglav C-162/13, on insurance for motorised vehicles used off-road and on private property.","false","Biography information for Sammy Wilson","East Antrim","Sammy Wilson","46349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583218","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-10","<p>It is the responsibility of train operators, as service providers, to ensure that their customers are made aware of their rights to compensation or other redress in cases of service failure or disruption. Train operators’ existing compensation schemes will continue to provide the main means of redress for passengers after 1 October 2016, when the Consumer Rights Act came into force for all transport providers.</p><p> </p><p>Information about the Consumer Rights Act is widely available from the Citizens Advice Consumer Service, consumer organisations and government websites.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-10T13:14:18.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583218/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583218/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-14","Railways: Commuters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to inform rail commuters of the protections available to them under the Consumer Rights Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","46478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583219","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Government remains committed to safeguarding the interests of public transport users, doing so (in addition to the work of the DfT) primarily through the following three bodies:</p><ul><li>The Office of Rail and Road, which protects rail passenger rights through licensing train operating companies and enforcing consumer protection law in the rail sector.</li><li>Transport Focus is responsible for representing the interests of Britain’s rail passengers as well as those of bus, coach and tram passengers in England (outside of London).</li><li>London TravelWatch, which is funded by the London Assembly, performs a similar role to that of Transport Focus for passengers in London.</li></ul><p> </p><p>The Government remains open-minded to considering any alternatives as to how these arrangements could be further improved in the future.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-10T11:13:27.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583219/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583219/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-14","Public Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make it his policy to establish a body with the remit of ensuring that the rights of public transport users are protected.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","46475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583220","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-10","<p>Tolling levels for the Mersey Tunnels and the future Mersey Gateway Crossing are the responsibility of the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority and Halton Borough Council respectively. Any assessment of the local impact of these tolls is therefore a matter for these bodies rather than this Department. The Department’s assessment of the business case for the Crossing included a consideration of the overall impacts effects of tolling levels on road users and showed that the new Crossing will reduce congestion and improve journey times for users. This assessment was not disaggregated to the level of individual local areas.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-10T13:49:11.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583220/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583220/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-14","Tolls: Merseyside","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of the tunnel and bridge tolls in Merseyside on the (a) finances, (b) employment levels, (c) employment choices and (d) road travel habits of residents of Liverpool, Wavertree.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","46483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583221","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-12","<p>The Government’s reforms simplify the system for claimants, helping move more people into work, and reduce the cost for taxpayers. Throughout these reforms the Government is ensuring that the vulnerable are protected. In every year to 2020 spending on disability will be higher than in 2010.</p><p>The Warm Home Discount scheme provides eligible households with a £140 energy bill rebate. This winter, almost a million low income working age households will be helped under the scheme.</p><p>We are also reforming the Energy Company Obligation to have a greater focus on vulnerable and low income households. It will have a value of £640m a year from 2017 until 2022 and could reduce the energy bills of those who receive energy efficiency improvements by up to £300 per year.</p><p>DWP provides help with the additional costs of heating during periods of severely cold weather to eligible claimants on certain income related benefits. In 2015-16, DWP made nearly 155,000 awards worth £3.9 million. For winter 2016/17 the cold weather payment rate will continue to be £25 for each seven day period of very cold weather.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-10-12T13:34:05.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583221/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583221/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-14","Social Security Benefits: Fuel Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if his Department will make an assessment of the effect of the Government's welfare reforms on low-income households who are in fuel poverty since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","46362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583222","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Green Paper will be published later this year, and we welcome feedback.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-10-10T14:55:53.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583222/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583222/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-14","Musculoskeletal Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the Government's planned Green Paper on disability employment will include proposals related to people with musculoskeletal conditions.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","46377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583223","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-10","<p>On 15 September I tabled a written statement saying that I had begun the consultation on this secondary legislation with the intention that the increase in the compensation cap will be implemented from April 2017.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2016-10-10T16:42:07.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583223/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583223/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-14","Pension Protection Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his Department's timetable is for publishing and implementing the secondary legislation required to implement the increase in the Pension Protection Fund compensation cap provided for under the Pensions Act 2014.","false","Biography information for David Warburton","Somerton and Frome","David Warburton","46437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583224","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-10","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>As part of the recent Machinery of Government changes, over the coming months we will be considering how to bring together the reform agendas of BEIS’s two predecessor Departments.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-10-10T13:59:32.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583224/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583224/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-14","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2016 to Question 43629, what plans he has to review the aspects of the BIS 2020 programme that do not relate to staff posts and office locations in the light of the restructuring of government departments.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","46435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583225","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-10","<p>Following the appointment of my rt. Hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy on 14 July 2016 all employees of the Department of Energy and Climate Change became part of the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy on that date.</p><p>There have been no redundancies made since the 14 July as a result of the machinery of government change.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-10-10T11:11:36.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583225/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583225/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-14","Department of Energy and Climate Change: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many officials of the Department for Energy and Climate Change have not transferred to work at his Department; and what the cost has been to date of redundancy payments to such staff resulting from the changes to the machinery of government.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","46365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583226","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-10","<p>A summary of the value for money analysis will be published alongside the contract and associated agreements when they have been entered into.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-10T11:12:25.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583226/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583226/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-14","Hinkley Point C Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will lay a revised departmental minute detailing the most recent estimate of costs of Hinkley Point C before Parliament; and if he will lay such a minute at least 14 days in advance of signing any binding contract for that project.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","46335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583227","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-10","<p>Innovate UK published its 2016/17 Delivery Plan in April 2016. This sets out measures to nurture high-growth potential SMEs and to work with universities and the research base across the UK to turn scientific excellence into economic impact. It includes joint programmes to promote collaboration between SMEs and the academic sector.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-10-10T15:16:14.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583227/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583227/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-14","Innovate UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans Innovate UK has to develop a business plan across the UK for liaison with universities on the promotion of greater innovation in private sector small and medium-sized enterprises.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","46355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583229","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-21","<p>The process for switching supplier is set out in industry codes, in the formulation of which the Government has no role. The Energy Switching Guarantee was launched in June this year and can be reached via <a href="https://www.energyswitchguarantee.com/" target="_blank">https://www.energyswitchguarantee.com/</a>. This makes switching energy supplier easier for consumers and guarantees that it will be done within 21 days. The guarantee also ensures that the new supplier will handle the whole transfer process for the consumer.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-21T12:43:00.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583229/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583229/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-14","Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will make it his policy that consumers who wish to switch energy providers only have to make contact with the new provider.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","46477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583230","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-13","<p>Ministers and officials in the Department for International Trade are working closely with counterparts across a wide range of markets, in order to promote the UK as a great place to do business and with which to trade. We are taking advantage of all the opportunities available to us to ensure that Britain becomes the global leader in free trade once we leave the EU.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-13T16:27:17.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583230/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583230/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-14","Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussions he has had with his counterparts in (a) China, (b) USA, Canada and Hong Kong, (c) Australia, (d) Brazil, (e) India, (f) South Korea, (g) Japan, (h) Mexico and (i) South Africa on negotiating trade deals with the UK.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","46469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583231","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-11","<p>The EU Canada Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement (CETA) will be laid before Parliament in due course.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-11T14:54:20.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583231/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583231/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-14","Trade Agreements: Canada","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, when he plans to lay the Comprehensive Economic Trade Agreement between the EU and Canada before Parliament.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","46479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583232","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-14","<p>A full list of all EU trade agreements can be found on the European Commission’s website (<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/countries-and-regions/agreements/index_en.htm" target="_blank">http://ec.europa.eu/trade/policy/countries-and-regions/agreements/index_en.htm</a>).</p><p>We recognise the need for a smooth transition as the UK leaves the EU which minimises disruption to our trading relationships. We will engage fully with all stakeholders over the coming weeks and months as we prepare for the negotiation with the EU and beyond.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-14T12:25:06.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583232/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583232/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-14","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate his Department has made of the number of agreements that will need to be renegotiated if the UK is no longer a member of the single market; and which trade agreements those agreements are.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","46440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583233","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-14","<p>Fifteen per cent of the UK’s exports of goods and services in 2014 went to countries with which the EU has negotiated free trade agreements (FTAs). This includes FTAs that have been implemented and those where negotiations have been completed but are still awaiting ratification. It does not include UK exports to EEA countries or non-EU members of the Customs Union.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-14T13:52:15.87Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583233/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583233/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-14","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate he has made of the total annual value to the UK of each trade deal to which the UK is a party as a consequence of the UK's membership of the European single market.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","46441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583234","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-13","<p>The Department for International Trade already has a strong and capable trade policy team which has more than doubled in size since 23 June. Over the coming months we will be developing that team to build the world class negotiating strengths needed to deliver the best outcomes for the UK. They will have the depth and breadth of expertise to handle the full range of sectoral and cross-cutting issues that arise in trade agreements, supported by analysts and lawyers.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-13T16:18:59.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583234/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583234/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-14","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking to determine how many trade negotiators his Department will require in the next six months.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","46432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583235","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-10","<p>The proportion of UK trade (exports and imports) with Australia, Canada, China, Singapore, the US and all EU member states in each of the last five years is given in the attached table. The estimates are based on data sourced from the latest Office for National Statistics’ Pink Book 2016 release.</p><p> </p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-10-10T16:12:29.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583235/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583235/answer","Final answer to PQ 23055 - Table 1.docx","Final answer to PQ 23055 - Table 1.docx","Proportion of UK Trade - Statistics","Proportion of UK Trade - Statistics","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583235/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-14","Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what proportion of UK trade was with (a) Germany, (b) France, (c) Italy, (d) Spain, (e) Australia, (f) China, (g) Singapore, (h) US, (i) Canada and (j) other EU member states in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","46408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583236","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear we will not give a running commentary on Brexit negotiations. We will ensure that we engage closely with all relevant interlocutors.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-10T16:14:06.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583236/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583236/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-14","Department for Exiting the European Union: Meetings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2016 to Question 45148, if he will estimate the number of meetings Ministers of his Department have had with their international counterparts to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","46424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583237","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-10","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given on 12 September 2016 to the Question 44967.</p><p> </p><p>The Prime Minister has been clear we will not give a running commentary on Brexit negotiations. We will ensure that we engage closely with all relevant interlocutors.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","46396","2016-10-10T16:10:44.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583237/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583237/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583237/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-14","Didier Seeuws","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with Didier Seeuws on the UK's exit of the EU since his appointment to the EU special task force.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","46395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583238","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-10","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given on 12 September 2016 to the Question 44967.</p><p> </p><p>The Prime Minister has been clear we will not give a running commentary on Brexit negotiations. We will ensure that we engage closely with all relevant interlocutors.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","46395","2016-10-10T16:10:44.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583238/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583238/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583238/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-14","Didier Seeuws","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many times he has met with Didier Seeuws since his appointment to the EU special task force.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","46396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583239","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear we will not give a running commentary on Brexit negotiations. We will ensure that we engage closely with all relevant interlocutors.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","46471","2016-10-10T16:13:00.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583239/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583239/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583239/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-14","Guy Verhofstadt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many times he has met with Guy Verhofstadt to discuss the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","46470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583240","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear we will not give a running commentary on Brexit negotiations. We will ensure that we engage closely with all relevant interlocutors.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","46470","2016-10-10T16:13:00.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583240/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583240/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583240/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-14","Guy Verhofstadt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with with Guy Verhofstadt on the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","46471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583241","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Department for Exiting the EU now has over 200 staff in London, plus the expertise of over 120 officials in Brussels, and we are still growing rapidly. The overall size and scope of the new department, including staffing and budget, are regularly reviewed. We will ensure we are appropriately staffed to deal with the task at hand.</p><p><br>The Department will include staff and officials from various departments across Government. The Department has already started drawing together expertise with staff from around 20 Departments and organisations from across Government.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-10T16:26:57.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583241/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583241/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583241/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-14","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 7 September 2016 to Question 44230, whether the staff in his Department are new employees or have been seconded from other Departments.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","46454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583242","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Department is permanently headquartered at 9 Downing Street.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-10T16:28:11.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583242/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583242/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583242/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-14","Department for Exiting the European Union: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, when he expects to have a permanent address for his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","46468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583431","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-26","<p>Our goal is to liberate Mosul, and eventually Raqqah, in a way that minimises the humanitarian impact, and supports political reconciliation and the return of local communities. We are engaging with the Government of Iraq and Kurdistan Regional Government, our Coalition partners, the UN and other international organisations to ensure comprehensive plans are in place which do this. On 21 July, the Foreign Secretary announced that the UK will lead a global campaign to bring Daesh to justice, including putting in place processes to assemble evidence for future legal proceedings.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-26T15:27:42.7Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583431/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583431/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-14","Islamic State","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the reply by Baroness Goldie on 13 September (HL Deb, col 1394), what plans are in place, once cities such as Mosul and Raqqa have been liberated from ISIS, to ensure the restoration of property, homes and businesses to their rightful owners, the re-establishment of diverse communities, and the creation of a legal framework to bring to trial those who have been responsible for genocide and ethnic cleansing.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583433","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-28","<p>We have made clear our deep concern at and condemnation of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) nuclear programme. We take into account all sources of information when assessing it. As the Parliamentary Under-Secretary for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Hon. Friend the Member for Reading West (Alok Sharma) made clear in his remarks to the UN Security Council on 23 September, that the United Kingdom condemns the recent nuclear test conducted by the DPRK, which is a direct violation of binding Security Council Resolutions. The DPRK must comply with its obligations under all relevant UN Security Council Resolutions, including abandoning all nuclear weapons and nuclear programmes in a complete, verifiable and irreversible manner.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-28T15:22:38.61Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583433/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583433/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-14","North Korea: Nuclear Weapons","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the report by Siegfried Hecker, published on 12 September, concluding that North Korea will have enough material for about 20 nuclear bombs by the end of this year, that it has expanded uranium enrichment facilities, and that it has stockpiled plutonium.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583434","Department for International Development","false","2016-09-27","<p>The UK supports organisations such as the UN through core contributions. UN agencies are delivering humanitarian assistance to people affected.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-09-27T13:53:02.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583434/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583434/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-14","North Korea: Floods","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what humanitarian aid they are providing to injured and displaced persons in North Korea following the recent flooding in that country.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583435","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-21","<p>The Government is considering Professor Waterson’s Review and will publish its response in due course.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-09-21T15:04:36.71Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583435/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583435/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-14","Consumer Protection Measures in the Ticket Resale Market Review","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they will respond to the Independent Review of Consumer Protection Measures concerning Online Secondary Ticketing Facilities published on 26 May.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL1901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583436","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-29","<p>The Government supports the use of Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR) to help businesses and consumers save time and money when dealing with complaints. Approved ADR is available for every consumer to trader dispute in the UK.</p><p>We have not estimated what proportion of retail businesses have a designated ADR provider as it is open to the retailer to choose a different ADR provider with the necessary skills and experience to deal with a particular dispute.</p><p>The Chartered Trading Standards Institute acts as the lead competent authority and has held working groups and individual meetings with the other competent authorities to ensure consistency of approach.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","HL1905","2016-09-29T15:19:40.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583436/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583436/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-14","Retail Trade: Dispute Resolution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the proportion of retail businesses that have designated an appropriate alternative dispute resolution (ADR) provider for their sector in accordance with the EU ADR Directive.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL1902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583437","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-29","<p>Responses to the call for evidence on the consumer landscape and quicker switching are still being considered. The Government will publish a summary of the responses in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-09-29T15:18:49.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583437/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583437/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-14","Consumers: Protection","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they plan to publish the responses to the call for evidence on improving the consumer landscape and quicker switching published by the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills in May.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL1903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583438","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-21","<p>In December 2015 the Government confirmed its intention to bring forward draft legislation to create a Public Service Ombudsman, encompassing the existing jurisdictions of the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman and the Local Government Ombudsman. The intention remains to publish a draft Bill in this parliamentary session.</p>",,"Baroness Mobarik",,"2016-09-21T14:12:26.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583438/answer","Biography information for Baroness Mobarik","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/583438/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-14","Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman: Local Government Ombudsman","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress they have made to bring together the work of the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman with that of the Local Government Ombudsman.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL1904"
